ies in Europe. A Comparative Analysis of Party Strategies for Auto</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E015352/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research programme examines the impact of European integration on substate demands for autonomy. The research explores how changing state and European structures have contributed to a more pronounced emphasis on territorial identities and interests, leading substate political parties to pursue autonomist strategies in Europe, in part inspired by the imagery of a ?Europe of the Regions?.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Whilst scholars have begun to examine the impact of European integration on national party politics, there are few analyses of Europe?s impact on regional party politics, and none that have examined how substate political parties have sought to enhance regional powers during a period in which state boundaries have become fuzzy. The research seeks to fill this gap by exploring how substate parties in Scotland, Bavaria and Sardinia have pursued territorial strategies to secure autonomy and capacity in Europe since the 1980s.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research addresses a number of questions: how integration has altered the nature of territorial politics and party competition; how the European dimension interacts with other drivers of territorial mobilisation, and the limitations of Europe for territorial projects. Based on a theoretical deepening of Hepburn?s doctoral research, The aim is to develop a theory of the politics of autonomy in Europe.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>66848</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>ECPR standing group on federalism and regionalism</gtr:description><gtr:form>A magazine, newsletter or online publication</gtr:form><gtr:id>11222C9D-EFF1-4D20-93DD-9E1E0FD2AE0A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Bi-annual newsletter of the European Consortium for Political Research (ECPR) standing group on federalism and regionalism</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-2897355493.99382972af5d452</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:year>2007</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>42A81767-7F19-466E-B135-BF5B05C8B325</gtr:id><gtr:title>Party politics in multi-level systems : party responses to new challenges in European democracies</gtr:title><gtr: